          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-direct-products"><title>Direct products</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.100">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>g_\alpha</m> be a group, and write <m>g_\alpha = \langle A_\alpha | R\alpha \rangle</m>, for each <m>\alpha</m>. 
                  The direct sum of the <m>g_\alpha</m> is the <m>group \oplus g_\alpha = \langle \cup \alpha A_\alpha | \cup \alpha R\alpha \cup\{ab = ba | a \in g_\alpha, b \in \alpha, \alpha \ne \beta \} \rangle</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <remark>
              <p>
                There are <m>3</m> views of <m>G \times H</m>: 
                Using presentations (if <m>G = \langle A | R \rangle</m> and <m>H = \langle B | S \rangle</m>, then <m>G \times H = \langle A \cup B | R \cup S \cup\{ab = ba | a \in A, b \in B\}\rangle</m>), 
                as a Cartesian product set with componentwise multiplication, 
