    <chapter xml:id="ch-covering"><title>Covering Spaces</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-liting"><title>Definitions and Lifting</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-defs"><title>Definition</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A covering space of a topological space <m>X</m> is a space <m>XÌƒ</m> together with a continuous function <m>p: XÌƒ \to X</m> satisfying: 
                There is an open covering <m>\{U\alpha \}</m> of <m>X</m> such that for all <m>\alpha</m> the preimage <m>p\inv(U\alpha )</m> is a disjoint union of open sets in <m>XÌƒ</m>, each of which is mapped (by the restriction of <m>p</m>) homeomorphically onto <m>U\alpha</m>. 
                Each set <m>U\alpha</m> is called evenly covered.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-thms"><title>Lifting Theorems</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.3"><title>PPHLT = Path and Path Homotopy Lifting Theorems</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be a covering space.

                <ul>
                  <li><title>PLT</title>
                    <p>
                      Given a path <m>f: (I,0) \to (X,x_0)</m>, there is a unique path <m>fÌƒ: (I,0) \to (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> such that <m>p \circ fÌƒ = f</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li><title>PHLT</title>
                    <p>
                      Given a path homotopy <m>H: (I \times I,(0,0)) \to (X,x_0)</m>, there is a unique path homotopy <m>HÌƒ: (I \times I,(0,0)) \to (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> such that<m> p \circ HÌƒ = H</m>. 
                      Moreover, if <m>H</m> is a path homotopy between two paths <m>f,g: (I,0) \to (X,x_0)</m>, then <m>HÌƒ</m> is a path homotopy between the "lifts" <m>fÌƒ,gÌƒ: (I,0) \to (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> of <m>f,g</m> from the PLT.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.4"><title>LC+ULP = Lifting Criterion and Unique Lifting Property</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be a covering space, let <m>Y</m> be a PC and LPC space, and let <m>f: (Y,y_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be continuous.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>fâˆ—(\pi_1(Y,y_0)) \sse pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0))</m>, then there is a unique continuous function <m>fÌƒ: (Y,y_0) \to (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> such that <m>p \circ fÌƒ = f</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>fâˆ—(\pi_1(Y,y_0)) âŠˆ pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0))</m>, then there does not exist a continuous lift <m>fÌƒ: (Y,y_0) \to (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> such that <m>p \circ fÌƒ = f</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> is a covering space, then the induced homomorphism <m>pâˆ—: \pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to \pi_1(X,x_0)</m> is injective (that is, <m>Ker pâˆ— =\{1\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)\}</m>), and the image satisfies <m>Im pâˆ— = pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)) =\{[f] \in \pi_1(X,x_0) | \text{ the lift } fÌƒ \text{ of }f \text{ at }xÌƒ_0 \text{ is a loop in }XÌƒ\}</m>. 
                Consequently, <m>\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)</m> is isomorphic to a subgroup of <m>\pi_1(X,x_0)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-group-apps"><title>Application to group theory</title>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For all <m>n \in \N</m>, the free group <m>Fn</m> is a subgroup of <m>F2</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The free group <m>F(S)</m> on a countably infinite set <m>S</m> is a subgroup of <m>F2</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-shhets"><title>The number of sheets</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be a covering space such that <m>X</m> and <m>XÌƒ</m> are PC. 
                The number of sheets of the covering space is <m>|p\inv({x_0\})|</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.11"><title>Lifting Correspondence</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be a covering space such that <m>X</m> and <m>XÌƒ</m> are PC. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The Lifting Correspondence Function <m>Î¦: \pi_1(X,x_0)/pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)) \to p\inv({x_0\})</m> defined by <m>Î¦(pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0))[f]) := fÌƒ(1)</m>, where <m>fÌƒ</m> is the unique lift of the loop <m>f</m> to a path in <m>XÌƒ</m> starting at <m>xÌƒ_0</m>, is a well-defined bijection.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For all points <m>x' \in X, |p\inv({x'\})| = |p\inv({x_0\})| = </m>(the number of sheets of<m> p</m>) <m>=</m> the index of <m>pâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0)) in \pi_1(X,x_0)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-int"><title>Interactions with functions and constructions:</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.18">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> is a covering space, then <m>p</m> is an open map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.20">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> be a covering space. 
                If <m>A</m> is a subspace of <m>X</m> and <m>Ãƒ := p\inv(A)</m>, then the restriction <m>p|AÃƒ:Ãƒ \to A</m> is also a covering space.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.21">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p_i:XÌƒ_i \to X_i</m> be covering spaces for <m>i \in\{1,2\}</m>. 
                Then <m>q := (p_1 \circ proj_1,p_2 \circ proj_2) :XÌƒ_1 \times XÌƒ_2 \to X_1 \times X_2 [\text{ that is}, q(S^1,S^2) := (p_1(S^1),p2(S^2)) \text{ for all }(S^1,S^2) \in XÌƒ_1 \times XÌƒ_2]</m> is also a covering space.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-inv"><title>Interactions with homeomorphism invariants:</title>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.25">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> be a covering space. 
                If <m>X</m> is a CW complex, then <m>XÌƒ</m> is a CW complex. 
                Moreover, <m>p</m> maps open <m>n</m>-cells to open <m>n</m>-cells for all <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.27">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> be a covering space satisfying the property that <m>p\inv({s\})</m> is finite and nonempty for all <m>s \in X</m>. 
                The space <m>XÌƒ</m> is compact and <m>T_2</m> if and only if the space <m>X</m> is compact and <m>T_2</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-actions"><title>Building Covering Spaces Using Group Actions</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-csga"><title>Covering space group actions</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given a group <m>G</m> and a topological space <m>Y</m>, an action of <m>G</m> on <m>Y</m> (or "action of <m>G</m> on <m>Y</m> by homeomorphisms") is a homomorphism <m>Ï:G \to Homeo(Y)</m>, where <m>Homeo(Y)</m> is the group of homeomorphisms <m>:Y \to Y</m> with group operation given by composition. 
                For each <m>g \in G</m> and <m>y \in Y</m>, denote <m>g Â· y := (Ï(g))(y)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.42">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given an action of a group <m>G</m> on a space <m>Y</m>, let <m>\sim G</m> be the equivalence relation on <m>Y</m> defined by <m>y \sim G y'</m> iff there is a <m>g \in G</m> with <m>g Â· y = y'</m> for all <m>y,y' \in Y</m>. 
                For each <m>y \in Y</m>, the equivalence class <m>[y] = [y]G = G Â· y</m> is called the orbit of <m>y</m>. 
                The quotient space <m>Y/\sim</m> is called the orbit space of the group action and denoted <m>Y/G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.44">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A covering space action of a group <m>G</m> on a space <m>Y</m> is an action satisfying: 
                For each <m>y \in Y</m> there is an open set <m>Uy</m> in <m>Y</m> containing <m>y</m> such that whenever <m>g,g' \in G</m> and <m>(g Â· Uy) \cap (g' Â· Uy) \ne \es</m> then <m>g = g'</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.45">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>G</m> has a covering space action on <m>Y</m>, then: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The quotient <m>p:Y \to Y/G</m> is a covering space. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>Y</m> is PC and LPC and <m>y_0 \in Y</m>, then <m>pâˆ—(\pi_1(Y,y_0)) âŠ´ \pi_1(Y/G,[y_0])</m> and <m>G \cong \pi_1(Y/G,[y_0]) / pâˆ—(\pi_1(Y,y_0))</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.46">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>Y</m> is an SC CW complex and <m>G</m> acts on <m>Y</m> with a covering space action, then <m>\pi_1(Y/G) \cong G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-building-cs"><title>Building SC covering spaces from group presentations</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.50">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\langle A | R \rangle</m> be a presentation of a group <m>G</m>. 
                The Cayley complex of this presentation is the CW complex <m>XÌƒ</m> constructed by: <m>XÌƒ(0) = G</m>. 
                The set of edges is in bijection with <m>G \times A</m>; for each <m>g \in G</m> and <m>a \in A</m>, the attaching map of the edge eg, <m>a</m> is <m>Ï†g,a(-1) = g</m> and <m>Ï†g,a(1) = ga</m>.
                The set of faces is in bijection with <m>G \times R</m>; for each <m>g \in G</m> and <m>r \in R</m>, the attaching map <m>Ï†g,r</m> of the face <m>fg,r</m> satisfies <m>Ï†g,r \circ Ï‰ := \text{ edge path in }XÌƒ(1)</m> starting at <m>g</m> labeled by <m>r</m>.
                The <m>1</m>-skeleton <m>XÌƒ(1)</m> is the Cayley graph of <m>G</m> with respect to <m>A</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.52">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\langle A | R \rangle</m> be a presentation of a group <m>G</m>, let <m>XÌƒ</m> be the Cayley complex, and let <m>X</m> be the presentation complex. 
                Then
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      the action of <m>G</m> on <m>XÌƒ</m>, given by <m>g Â· h := (gh), g Â· eh,a := e(gh),a</m>, and <m>g Â· fh,r := f(gh),r</m> for all <m>h \in G</m>, <m>a\in A</m>, and <m>r \in R</m>, is a covering space action;
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>XÌƒ</m> is a SC CW complex (and hence PC, LPC, and SLSC), and hence <m>\pi_1(XÌƒ/G) \cong G</m>; and 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>XÌƒ/G \cong X</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-existence"><title>Existence of covering spaces</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.60">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a PC, LPC, SLSC space and <m>x_0 \in X</m>. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (SC Covering Space Thm): There is a SC covering space <m>p:(XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m>, and there is covering space group action of <m>G := \pi_1(X,x_0)</m> on <m>XÌƒ</m> that induces <m>p</m>; hence <m>(XÌƒ/G,[xÌƒ_0]) \cong (X,x_0)</m>. 
                      Moreover, if <m>X</m> is a CW complex, then <m>XÌƒ</m> is a CW complex, and for each open <m>n</m>-cell \sigma of <m>X</m> there are <m>|G|</m> open <m>n</m>-cells of <m>XÌƒ</m> mapping via <m>p</m> to <m>\sigma</m> such that the action of each <m>g \in G</m> on <m>XÌƒ</m> permutes these <m>n</m>-cells.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Covering Space Existence Thm): For each subgroup <m>H &lt; \pi_1(X,x_0)</m>, there is a covering space <m>rH: (XÌƒ/H,[xÌƒ_0]H) \to (X,x_0)</m> such that <m>rH \circ qH = p</m>, where <m>qH: XÌƒ \to XÌƒ/H</m> is the quotient map, and <m>H = rHâˆ—(\pi_1(XÌƒ/H,[xÌƒ_0]H))</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.67">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>(X,x_0)</m> is a PC, LPC, SLSC space or PC CW complex, <m>H &lt; \pi_1(X,x_0)</m>, and <m>rH:(XÌƒ/H,[xÌƒ_0]H) \to (X,x_0)</m> is the covering space of Thm 6.60(b), then the number of sheets of this covering space is the index of <m>H</m> in <m>\pi_1(X,x_0)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-build-pres"><title>Building covering spaces for subgroups from group presentations</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.70">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\langle A | R \rangle</m> be a presentation of a group <m>G</m> and let <m>X</m> be the presentation complex with vertex <m>x_0</m>. 
                Let <m>H &lt; G</m>.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Top-down Method): Let <m>XÌƒ</m> be the Cayley complex of the presentation with quotient map <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m>. 
                      Then <m>H</m> has a covering space action on <m>XÌƒ</m>, with quotient map <m>qH:XÌƒ \to XÌƒ/H</m>, and the covering space <m>rH:XÌƒ/H \to X</m> defined by <m>rH([s]H) := p(s)</m> for all <m>[s]H \in XÌƒ/H</m> satisfies <m>Im rHâˆ— = H</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Bottom-up Method): Let <m>Z</m> be the CW complex constructed by: <m>Z(0) := H\G</m> (the set of right cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>). 
                      The set of edges of <m>Z</m> is in bijection with <m>H\G \times A</m>; for each <m>Hg \in H\G</m> and <m>a \in A</m>, the attaching map of the edge <m>eHg</m>,<m>a</m> is <m>Ï†Hg,a(-1) = Hg and Ï†Hg,a(1) = Hga</m>. 
                      The set of faces of <m>Z</m> is in bijection with <m>H\G \times R</m>; for each <m>Hg \in H\G</m> and <m>r \in R</m>, the attaching map <m>Ï†Hg,r</m> of the face <m>fHg,r</m> satisfies <m>Ï†Hg,r \circ Ï‰ :=</m> edge path in <m>Z(1)</m> starting at <m>Hg</m> labeled by <m>r</m>. 
                      Then <m>r:Z \to X</m> such that <m>r(Hg) = x_0, r(eHg,a) = </m>the edge of <m>X</m> corresponding to <m>a</m>, and <m>r(fHg,r) =</m> the face of <m>X</m> corresponding to <m>r</m> (for all <m>Hg, a</m>, and <m>r</m>) is a covering space and <m>Im râˆ— = H</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-apps"><title>Applications to group theory</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.75">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every subgroup of a free group is a free group.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.77">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>H</m> be a finite index subgroup of a group <m>G</m>. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>G</m> is a finitely generated group, then <m>H</m> is also finitely generated.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>G</m> is a finitely presented group, then <m>H</m> is also finitely presented.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>
        
      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-galois-cor"><title>The Universal Covering and Galois Correspondence</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.80">
          <statement>
            <p>
              An isomorphism of pointed covering spaces <m>pi: (Yi,yi) \to (X,x_0)</m> for <m>i=1,2</m> is a homeomorphism <m>f:(Y1,y1) \to (Y2,y2)</m> such that <m>p2 \circ f = p1</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-6.81"><title>Covering Space Uniqueness Theorem</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Any two PC, LPC pointed covering spaces <m>pi: (Yi,yi) \to (X,x_0)</m> (for <m>i=1,2</m>) of a pointed space <m>(X,x_0)</m> satisfy<m> p1âˆ—(Y1,y1) = p2âˆ—(Y2,y2)</m> iff the pointed covering spaces are isomorphic.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.82">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>X</m> be a PC, LPC, SLSC space. 
              The universal covering space of <m>X</m> is the unique covering space <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> such that <m>XÌƒ</m> is SC.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.85">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A deck transformation of a covering space <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> is a homeomorphism <m>f:XÌƒ \to XÌƒ</m> such that <m>p \circ f = p</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.86">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A covering space <m>p:XÌƒ \to X</m> is normal if for all <m>y,y' \in XÌƒ</m> with <m>p(y) = p(y')</m>, there is a deck transformation <m>f:(XÌƒ,y) \to (XÌƒ,y')</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-6.88">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>(X,x_0)</m> be a PC, LPC, SLSC space, let <m>G := \pi_1(X,x_0)</m>, and let <m>p: (XÌƒ,xÌƒ_0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be the SC covering. 
              Let <m>r: (Z,z0) \to (X,x_0)</m> be any PC covering space. Then:
              <ol>
                <li><title>Galois Correspondence Thm</title>
                  <p>
                    The maps <m>\{\text{subgroups }H \text{ of }G\} â†”\{\text{isomorphism classes of PC pointed coverings of }(X,x_0)\}</m> defined by
                    <m>H \to (rH: (XÌƒ/H,[xÌƒ_0]H) \to (X,x_0))</m> and
                    <m>(t: (Y,y_0) \to (X,x_0)) \to Im tâˆ— = tâˆ—(\pi_1(Y,y_0))</m>
                    are inverse bijections.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li><title>Universal Covering Thm</title>
                  <p>
                    There is a covering space map <m>q: XÌƒ \to Z</m> such that <m>r \circ q = p</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li><title>Action Thm</title>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>H := râˆ—(\pi_1(Z,z0))</m> and let <m>NG(H) :=</m> the normalizer of <m>H</m> in <m>G :=\{ g \in G | gHg-1 \sse H \}</m>. 
                    The group of deck transformations of <m>r: Z \to X</m> is isomorphic to <m>NG(H)/H</m> and has a covering space action on <m>Z</m>. 
                    Moreover, (<m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>) iff (<m>G/H</m> has a covering space action on <m>Z</m> inducing <m>r</m>) iff (the covering space <m>r:Z \to X</m> is normal).
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <remark>
          <p>
            A Galois correspondence table has columns for spaces, fundamental groups, and covering space group actions. 
            Each row of contains a space <m>X</m>, <m>\pi_1(X)</m>, and the (deck transformation) group that acts on <m>X</m> with covering space group action (and is maximal with respect to that property).
            In the column of spaces, a space <m>Y</m> appears in a row above a space <m>X</m> if there is a covering space : <m>Y \to X</m>.
          </p>
        </remark>

        <example>
          <p>
            Examples
          </p>
        </example>
        
      </section>
      
