    <chapter xml:id="ch-homology"><title>Homology</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-simplicial"><title>Simplicial Homology</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-hom-overview"><title>Overview of Homotopy and Homology</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a topological space and <m>x_0 \in X</m>, and let <m>n \geq 1</m> be a natural number. 
                The <m>n</m>-th homotopy group of <m>X</m> at <m>x_0</m>, denoted <m>\pi n(X,x_0)</m>, is the set of homotopy classes of maps <m>(In,Bd\R^n(In)) \to (X,x_0)</m> with group operation defined by <m>[f][g] = [f âˆ— g]</m> for all <m>[f],[g] \in \pi n(X,x_0)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.2">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a space and <m>x_0 \in X</m>. 
                For all <m>n \geq 2</m>, the group <m>\pi n(X,x_0)</m> is abelian.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <p>
            Motivation: For dimensions <m>n \geq 2</m>, the group <m>\pi n(X,x_0)</m> is often difficult to compute. 
            Instead, define abelian groups <m>H_n(X)</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m> that capture much of the same information.
          </p>

          <p>
            Motivation: Define homology groups 3 ways: 
            simplicial homology <m>Hn\delta</m>  on <m>\delta</m> -complexes, cellular homology <m>HnCW</m> on CW-complexes, and singular homology <m>Hnsing</m> on topological spaces.
           \{\delta -complexes\} âŠŠ\{CW complexes\} âŠŠ\{topological spaces\}.
            <m>Hn\delta</m>  is easiest to compute, <m>HnCW</m> is harder to compute but easier to find the complex structure, and <m>Hnsing</m> is hardest to compute but easiest to use for proving theorems.
            For a <m>\delta</m>-complex <m>X</m>, <m>Hn\delta (X) = HnCW(X) = Hnsing(X)</m>.
            <m>Hn\delta</m>, <m>HnCW</m>, and <m>Hnsing</m> are all homotopy invariants.
          </p>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-delta"><title>\delta -Complexes</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                In <m>\R^n+1</m>, the <m>i</m>-th standard basis vector is <m>\varepsilon i(n) := (0,0,\dots,0,1,0,\dots,0)</m>, where the coordinates are indexed by <m>0,\dots,n</m> and the <m>1</m> appears in the <m>i</m>-th coordinate.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.11">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The standard <m>n</m>-simplex is the subspace of <m>\R^n+1</m> (with the Euclidean topology) given by <m>\delta n :=\{\sum i=0n ti\varepsilon i(n) | \sum i=0n ti = 1 \text{ and }0 \leq ti \leq 1 \text{ for all }i\}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.12">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The boundary of the standard <m>n</m>-simplex is the subspace <m>âˆ‚\delta n :=\{\sum i=0n ti\varepsilon i(n) | \sum i=0n ti = 1, 0 \leq ti \leq 1 \text{ for all }i, \text{ and }tj = 0 \text{ for some }j\}</m>.
                The open <m>n</m>-simplex is the subspace <m>0\delta n := \delta n - âˆ‚ \delta n</m> for <m>n \geq 1</m>, and <m>0\delta 0 := \delta 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.15">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For <m>0 \leq i \leq n</m>, the <m>i</m>-th face map of the standard <m>n</m>-simplex is the function <m>Fi(n): \delta n-1 \into  \delta n</m> defined by <m>Fi(n)(\sum i=0n-1 ti\varepsilon i(n-1)) := \sum j=0i-1 tj\varepsilon j(n) + \sum j=i+1n tj-1\varepsilon j(n)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.20">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A <m>\delta</m> -complex is a topological space <m>X</m> constructed inductively by:
                Let <m>X(0)</m> be a set of points with the discrete topology. 
                Write <m>X(0) = âˆ\alpha \in J0 \delta \alpha 0</m>, where for each <m>\alpha, \delta \alpha 0 \cong \delta 0</m>. 
                For each <m>\alpha \in J0</m>, let <m>\sigma Ì„\alpha 0: \delta \alpha 0 \to X(0)</m> be the inclusion map.
              </p>

              <p>
                For each <m>n \geq 1</m>, form the space <m>X(n)</m> from <m>X(n-1)</m> by:
                For each <m>\alpha</m> in an index set <m>Jn</m>, let <m>\delta \alpha n</m> be a copy of the standard <m>n</m>-simplex <m>\delta n</m>, and let <m>s\alpha : âˆ‚\delta \alpha n \to X(n-1)</m> be a continuous function such that for all <m>0 \leq i \leq n</m>, <m>s\alpha \circ Fi(n)|âˆ‚\delta n = \sigma Ì„\beta n-1</m> for some <m>\beta \in Jn-1</m>. 
                Let <m>Zn := X(n-1) âˆ (âˆ\alpha \in Jn \delta \alpha n)</m> have the disjoint union topology, and let <m>\sim</m> be the minimal equivalence relation on this space such that <m>d \sim s\alpha (d)</m> for all <m>d \in âˆ‚\delta \alpha n</m> and <m>\alpha \in Jn</m>. 
                Define <m>X(n)</m> be the quotient space and let qn be the quotient map. 
                Define <m>\sigma Ì„\alpha n: \delta \alpha n \to X(n)</m> to be the composition <m>\sigma Ì„\alpha n := qn \circ i\delta \alpha nZn</m> where <m>i\delta \alpha nZn: \delta \alpha n \to Zn</m> is the inclusion map.
                Let <m>X := \cup n \in \N  X(n)</m> (where each <m>X(n)</m> is identified with its image in <m>X(n+1)</m>). 
                For all <m>n</m> and for all <m>\alpha \in Jn</m>, define <m>\sigma \alpha n = \sigma \alpha : \delta \alpha n \to X</m> by <m>\sigma \alpha n := iX(n)X \circ \sigma Ì„\alpha n</m> where <m>iX(n)X: X(n) \to X</m> is the inclusion. 
                A subset <m>A</m> of <m>X</m> is defined to be open in <m>X</m> if and only if <m>(\sigma \alpha n)-1(A)</m> is open in <m>\delta \alpha n</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m> and all <m>\alpha \in Jn</m>.
                Each <m>\sigma \alpha n</m> is called an <m>n</m>-simplex of <m>X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-7.22">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every <m>\delta</m> -complex is a CW complex.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.24">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A topological space <m>X</m> has a <m>\delta</m> -complex structure if and only if there is a collection of continuous maps <m>\cC =\{\sigma \alpha :\delta n\alpha \to X\}</m> such that: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Each restriction <m>\sigma \alpha |(0\delta n\alpha )</m> is an embedding and each point of <m>X</m> is in the image of exactly one <m>\sigma \alpha | (0\delta n\alpha )</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Each <m>\sigma \alpha \circ Fi(n\alpha )</m> is a map <m>\sigma \beta : \delta n\alpha -1 \to X </m> in <m>\cC</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A subset <m>A</m> of <m>X</m> is open in <m>X</m> if and only if <m>\sigma \alpha -1(A)</m> is open in <m>\delta n\alpha</m> for all <m>\sigma \alpha</m> in <m>\cC</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-simp"><title>Simplicial Homology</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.30">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a <m>\delta</m> -complex and let <m>n \geq 0</m>. 
                The group of simplicial <m>n</m>-chains of <m>X</m> is <m>Cn\delta (X) := \oplus \alpha \in Jn \Z = \oplus n-simplices \sigma \alpha \Z \sigma \alpha</m>. 
                An element of <m>Cn\delta (X)</m> is called a (simplicial) <m>n</m>-chain, and written <m>\sum \alpha \in Jn m\alpha \sigma \alpha</m>, where each <m>m\alpha \in \Z</m> and all but finitely many <m>m\alpha</m>'s are <m>0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.32">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a <m>\delta</m> -complex and let <m>n \geq 1</m>. 
                The <m>n</m>-th simplicial boundary map is the group homomorphism <m>âˆ‚n\delta  = âˆ‚n: Cn\delta (X) \to Cn-1\delta (X)</m> defined by <m>âˆ‚n(\sum \alpha \in Jn m\alpha \sigma \alpha ) := \sum \alpha \in Jn m\alpha âˆ‚n(1\sigma \alpha )</m> and <m>âˆ‚n(1\sigma \alpha ) := \sum i=0n (-1)i \sigma \alpha \circ Fi(n)</m>.
                The <m>0</m>-th simplicial boundary map is the group homomorphism <m>âˆ‚0\delta  = âˆ‚0: C0\delta (X) \to 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-7.35">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a <m>\delta</m> -complex and <m>n \geq 1</m>, then <m>Im âˆ‚n+1\delta  \sse Ker âˆ‚n\delta</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.36">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a <m>\delta</m> -complex and let <m>n \geq 0</m>. 
                The <m>n</m>-th simplicial homology group of <m>X</m> is the group <m>Hn\delta (X) := Ker âˆ‚n\delta  / Im âˆ‚n+1\delta</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              A quotient of the form <m>\Z n/\Z m</m> is not well-defined.
              In order to compute this quotient, write the elements of a basis of <m>\Z m</m> as linear combinations of the elements of a basis of <m>\Z n</m>: compute the Smith normal form.    
            </p>
          </remark>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-7.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\{a1,\dots,ak\}</m>, viewed as an ordered list, be a basis for <m>\Z k</m>. 
                Then each of the following operations creates another basis for this group:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Swap two of the basis elements <m>(ai â†” aj)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Multiply a basis element by <m>-1 (ai \to -ai)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Add an integral multiple of one basis element to another <m>(ai \to ai+maj)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
          
        </subsection>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-sing-hom"><title>Singular Homology</title>

        <introduction>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <q>
                ...Commutative algebra is a lot like topology, only backwards.
              </q>
            </p>
            <attribution>John Baez</attribution>
          </blockquote>
        </introduction>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-induced-hom"><title>Definitions and Induced Homomorphisms</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.50">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. 
                A singular <m>n</m>-simplex of <m>X</m> is a continuous function <m>\sigma :\delta n \to X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.51">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a topological space and let <m>n \geq 0</m>. 
                Let <m>Sn</m> be the set of singular <m>n</m>-simplices of <m>X</m>. 
                The group of singular <m>n</m>-chains of <m>X</m> is <m>Cnsing(X) = Cn(X) := \oplus singular n-simplices \sigma \Z = \oplus singular n-simplices \sigma \Z \sigma</m>. 
                An element of <m>Cnsing(X)</m> is called a (singular) <m>n</m>-chain, and written <m>\sum singular n-simplices \sigma m\sigma \sigma</m>, where each <m>m\sigma \in \Z</m> and all but finitely many <m>m\sigma</m>'s are <m>0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.52">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a topological space and let <m>n \geq 1</m>. 
                The <m>n</m>-th singular boundary map is the group homomorphism <m>âˆ‚nsing = âˆ‚nX = âˆ‚n: Cnsing(X) \to Cn-1sing(X)</m> defined by <m>âˆ‚n(\sum singular n-simplices \sigma m\sigma \sigma ) := \sum singular n-simplices \sigma m\sigma âˆ‚n(1\sigma ) and âˆ‚n(1\sigma ) := \sum i=0n (-1)i \sigma \circ Fi(n)</m>.
                The <m>0</m>-th singular boundary map is the group homomorphism <m>âˆ‚0sing = âˆ‚0: C0sing(X) \to 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-7.55">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a topological space and <m>n \geq 1</m>, then <m>Im âˆ‚n+1sing \sse Ker âˆ‚nsing</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.56">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a topological space and let <m>n \geq 0</m>. 
                The <m>n</m>-th singular homology group of <m>X</m> is the group <m>Hnsing(X) = H_n(X) := Ker âˆ‚nsing / Im âˆ‚n+1sing</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-7.58">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a space with exactly one point, then <m>H_0(X) = \Z</m> and <m>Hn = 0</m> for all <m>n \geq 1</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.60">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If a space <m>X</m> has path components <m>X_\alpha</m>, then <m>Hnsing(X) = \oplus \alpha Hnsing(X_\alpha )</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.62">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a path-connected space, then <m>H0sing(X) \cong \Z</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <paragraphs><title>Excursion into homological algebra</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.70">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A chain complex, denoted <m>Câ€¢</m>, is a sequence <m>\cdots \to Cn+1 \to Cn \to Cn-1 \to \cdots C0 \to 0</m> with group homomorphisms <m>âˆ‚nC = âˆ‚n: Cn \to Cn-1</m> and <m>âˆ‚0C = âˆ‚0: C0 \to 0</m> satisfying <m>Im âˆ‚n+1 \sse Ker âˆ‚n</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                  An element of <m>Ker âˆ‚n</m> is called an <m>n</m>-cycle and an element of <m>Im âˆ‚n+1</m> is an <m>n</m>-boundary.
                  For <m>n \geq 0</m>, the <m>n</m>-th homology group of <m>Câ€¢ is H_n(Câ€¢) := Ker âˆ‚nC / Im âˆ‚n+1C</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.72">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A chain map from a chain complex <m>Câ€¢</m> to a chain complex <m>Dâ€¢</m>, written <m>fâ™¯:Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m>, is a collection of group homomorphisms <m>fnâ™¯: Cn \to Dn</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m> satisfying <m>âˆ‚nD \circ fnâ™¯ = fn-1â™¯ \circ âˆ‚nC</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.73">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>fâ™¯:Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> be a chain map. 
                  The <m>n</m>-th homology homomorphism induced by <m>fâ™¯</m> is the function <m>fnâˆ—: H_n(Câ€¢) \to H_n(Dâ€¢)</m> defined by <m>fnâˆ—(Î³ + Im âˆ‚n+1C) := fnâ™¯(Î³) + Im âˆ‚n+1D</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-7.74">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>fâ™¯:Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> is a chain map, then the <m>n</m>-th homology homomorphism <m>fnâˆ—</m> induced by <m>fâ™¯</m> is a well-defined group homomorphism.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.77">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Two chain maps <m>fâ™¯,gâ™¯: Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> are chain homotopic, written <m>fâ™¯ \simeq gâ™¯</m>, if there is a collection of group homomorphisms <m>hn: Cn \to Dn+1 </m>satisfying <m>gn - fn = âˆ‚n+1D \circ hn + hn-1 \circ âˆ‚nC</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                  The collection of functions <m>\{hn\}</m> is called a chain homotopy from <m>fâ™¯</m> to <m>gâ™¯</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-7.78">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>fâ™¯,gâ™¯: Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> are chain homotopic chain maps, then <m>fnâˆ— = gnâˆ—</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.80">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A chain map <m>fâ™¯: Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> is a chain homotopy equivalence if there is a chain map <m>gâ™¯: Dâ€¢ \to Câ€¢</m> such that <m>fâ™¯ \circ gâ™¯ \simeq 1Dâ€¢</m> and <m>gâ™¯ \circ fâ™¯ \simeq 1Câ€¢</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-7.82">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>fâ™¯: Câ€¢ \to Dâ€¢</m> is a chain homotopy equivalence, then <m>fnâˆ—: H_n(Câ€¢) \to H_n(Dâ€¢)</m> is an isomorphism for all <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>
            
          </paragraphs>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.90">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a <m>\delta</m> -complex, then <m>Hn\delta (X) \cong Hnsing(X)</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-7.91">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a topological space with two <m>\delta</m> -complex structures <m>X'</m> and <m>X''</m>, then <m>Hn\delta (X') \cong Hn\delta (X'')</m> for all <m>n \geq 0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <definition xml:id="def-7.95">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces and let <m>f:X \to Y</m> be a continuous function, and let <m>n \geq 0</m>. 
                The <m>n</m>-th homology homomorphism induced by <m>f</m> is the homology homomorphism <m>fnâˆ—: H_n(X) \to H_n(Y)</m> induced by the (induced) chain map <m>fâ™¯: Câ€¢sing(X) \to Câ€¢sing(Y)</m> defined by <m>fnâ™¯(\sum singular n-simplices \sigma of X m\sigma \sigma ) := \sum singular n-simplices \sigma</m> of <m>X m\sigma f \circ \sigma</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-7.96">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are topological spaces and <m>f:X \to Y</m> is a continuous function, then the induced chain map <m>fâ™¯</m> is a well-defined chain map and hence the induced homology homomorphisms are well-defined homomorphisms.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-7.97">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>f: X \to Y</m> and <m>g: Y \to Z</m> are continuous then <m>(g \circ f)nâˆ— = gnâˆ— \circ fnâˆ—</m> for all <m>n</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>(1X)nâˆ— = 1H_n(X)</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are homotopic maps, then <m>fnâˆ— = gnâˆ—</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.99">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are homotopy equivalent spaces (that is, <m>X \simeq Y</m>), then <m>H_n(X) \cong H_n(Y)</m> for all <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-7.100">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>X</m> is a contractible space, then <m>H_0(X) \cong \Z</m> and <m>H_n(X) = 0</m> for all <m>n \geq 1</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-decomp"><title>Decomposing Spaces and Homology Groups</title>

          <p>
            Motivation: Want an SVK theorem for homology
          </p>

          <paragraphs><title>Another excursion into homological algebra:</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.105">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A sequence of <m>Ï†:A \to B</m>, <m>\theta :B \to C</m> of groups and homomorphisms is exact at <m>B</m> if <m>Im Ï† = Ker \theta </m>. 
                  A sequence <m>\cdots Dn+1 \to Dn \to \cdots </m> is exact if it is exact at every group.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-7.106">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        A sequence <m>Ï†:A \to B</m>, <m>\theta :B \to 0</m> is exact if and only if <m>Ï†</m> is onto. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        A sequence <m>Ï†:0 \to B, \theta :B \to C</m> is exact if and only if <m>\theta </m> is one-to-one. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>A \to B \to C \to D \to E</m> is an exact sequence with homomorphisms <m>Ï†:A \to B</m> and <m>Ïˆ:D \to E</m> satisfying <m>Im Ï† = B</m> and <m>Ker Ïˆ = 0</m>, then <m>C = 0</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>
            
            
          </paragraphs>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-7.111"><title>MV = Mayer-Vietoris Theorem</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>X</m> is a topological space with subspaces <m>A,B</m> such that <m>X = Int(A) \cup Int(B)</m>. 
                Then there is an exact sequence <m>\cdots \to H_n(A \cap B) \to H_n(A) \oplus H_n(B) \to H_n(X) \to Hn-1(A \cap B) \to \cdots \to H_0(X) \to 0</m>, such that each homorphism <m>Ï†n: H_n(A \cap B) \to H_n(A) \oplus H_n(B)</m> is given by <m>Ï†n := (iAB nâˆ—,-iBA nâˆ—)</m> and each homomorphism <m>Ïˆn: H_n(A) \oplus H_n(B) \to H_n(X)</m> is given by <m>Ïˆn := jA nâˆ— + jB nâˆ—</m>, where <m>iAB: A \cap B \to A</m>, <m>iBA: A \cap B \to B</m>, <m>jA: A \to X</m>, and <m>jB: B \to X</m> are inclusion maps.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-7.115">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>H_i(Sn) \cong \Z</m> for <m>i = 0,n</m>, and <m>H_i(Sn) = 0</m> for all <m>i \ne 0,n</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <paragraphs><title>Yet another excursion into homological algebra</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.120">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A short exact sequence of chain complexes is a sequence <m>0â€¢ \to Aâ€¢ \to Bâ€¢ \to Câ€¢ \to 0â€¢</m> of chain complexes and chain maps such that for all <m>n \geq 0</m> the sequence <m>0 \to An \to Bn \to Cn \to 0</m> of groups and homomorphisms is exact.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-7.122"><title>Zig-zag Lemma</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>0_â€¢ \to A_â€¢, iâ™¯:A_â€¢ \to B_â€¢, jâ™¯:B_â€¢ \to C_â€¢, C_â€¢ \to 0</m> is a short exact sequence of chain complexes, then there is a (long) exact sequence <m>\cdots H_n(A) \to H_n(B) \to H_n(C) \to H_{n-1}(A) \to \cdots ,</m> with homomorphisms <m>inâˆ—:H_n(A) \to H_n(B)</m> and <m>jnâˆ—:H_n(B) \to H_n(C)</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>
            
          </paragraphs>

          <paragraphs><title>Proof of the MV Theorem</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-7.125">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a topological space with subspaces <m>A,B</m> such that <m>X = Int(A) \cup Int(B)</m>. 
                  The chain complex <m>C_â€¢(A+B)</m> is defined by: <m>C_n(A+B) := {\sum m\sigma \sigma + \sum kÏ„Ï„ | \text{ each }\sigma ,Ï„ \text{ is a singular} n-\text{ simplex of }X, \text{ each }\sigma (\delta n) \sse A \text{ and }Ï„(\delta n) \sse B, \text{ and each }m\sigma , kÏ„ \in \Z }</m> and <m>âˆ‚nA+B := âˆ‚nX|Cn(A+B)Cn-1(A+B)</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-7.127">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a topological space with subspaces <m>A,B</m> such that <m>X = Int(A) \cup Int(B)</m>. 
                  The sequence <m>0_â€¢ \to C_â€¢(A \cap B) \to C_â€¢(A) \oplus C_â€¢(B) \to C_â€¢(A+B) \to 0â€¢</m>, with homomorphisms <m>Ï†Ìƒ_n: C_n(A \cap B) \to C_n(A) \oplus C_n(B)</m> given by <m>Ï†Ìƒ_n := (i_{AB} nâ™¯,-i_{BA} nâ™¯) and ÏˆÌƒ_n: C_n(A) \oplus C_n(B) \to C_n(A+B)</m> given by <m>ÏˆÌƒ_n := jA nâ™¯ + jB nâ™¯</m>, is exact.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-7.130"><title>Small Chains Theorem</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a topological space with subspaces <m>A,B</m> such that <m>X = Int(A) \cup Int(B)</m>. 
                  Then <m>H_n(X) \cong H_n(A+B)</m> for all <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>           
            
          </paragraphs>

